{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":33239,"name":"Peter","username":"Spongeloaf","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/spongeloaf/{size}/2527_2.png","created_at":"2019-08-30T18:11:45.816Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThis is my first game project, coming from a world of scripting and microcontroller programming. This is reasonably different than anything Iâ€™ve done before. I need a sanity check, please.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMy game is all in 2d. It has a few basic types of objects. Planets, space rocks, missiles, and explosions. Iâ€™m using a custom component called â€œActorâ€ to store information and set basic behaviors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFor example, if a missile collides with a planet, it should simply be destroyed. If a missile collides with a space rock, it detonates and pushes the rock with a physics force. If a missile collides with a detonation, it should also be pushed, but not detonated. There are a few more basic behaviors but thatâ€™s enough for now.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIâ€™m concerned that the way Iâ€™m handling these different cases is clunky and over-thought. Iâ€™m handling collision events by subscribing to \u003ccode\u003eE_PHYSICSBEGINCONTACT2D\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eE_PHYSICSUPDATECONTACT2D\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eE_PHYSICSENDCONTACT2D\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI call a function and pass in eventtype \u0026amp; eventdata, and unpack the roles as follows:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003eNode* na = static_cast\u0026lt;Node*\u0026gt;(eventData[P_NODEA].GetPtr());\nNode* nb = static_cast\u0026lt;Node*\u0026gt;(eventData[P_NODEB].GetPtr());\n\nActor* aa = na-\u0026gt;GetComponent\u0026lt;Actor\u0026gt;();\nActor* ab = nb-\u0026gt;GetComponent\u0026lt;Actor\u0026gt;();\n\t\nRoles ra = aa-\u0026gt;get_role();\nRoles rb = ab-\u0026gt;get_role();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThen I pass them through a matrix of if-statements. This is the part I fear is clunky and over thought. The following example is just two cases, but there are at least 25 of them, and it goes up exponentially if I add more roles. Because in any collision between two different nodes, either one may be A or B, I need two cases for a missile colliding with a rock. (NODEA == missle \u0026amp;\u0026amp; NODEB == rock) or (NODEA == rock \u0026amp;\u0026amp; NODEB == missile).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHereâ€™s what that looks like:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003e// Roles are enums. \n// There are currently 25 of these if statements to cover all cases \n\nif ((ra == Roles::ROCK) \u0026amp;\u0026amp; (rb == Roles::MISSILE))\n{\n\t// detonate missile\n}\n\nif ((ra == Roles::MISSILE) \u0026amp;\u0026amp; (rb == Roles::ROCK))\n{\n\t// detonate missile\n}\n\nif ((ra == Roles::ROCK) \u0026amp;\u0026amp; (rb == Roles::ROCK))\n{\n\t// do nothing. The physics engine will handle bouncing.\n        // There's only a few \"Do nothing\" cases. I could get rid of them, but it would not trim a lot of fat\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOf course that could be condensed to only one if statement with a few extra parentheses thrown in there, but Iâ€™m just not sure I like this solution. The problem is I canâ€™t see any other effective method. If I add another role, that makes the number of if statements skyrocket because I have N^2 cases. It works, but it seems veryâ€¦derpy.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIs this a reasonable solution? Would you question my sanity if you saw this in production? Do you have some other ideas? Is there some feature of the engine to facilitate this procedure that Iâ€™m not aware of? Should I just shutup and get back to work?\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-08-30T22:24:40.032Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":43,"readers_count":42,"score":38.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"Peter","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1219,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33240,"name":"Actually Permanent","username":"throwawayerino","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/t/da6949/{size}.png","created_at":"2019-08-30T21:06:06.280Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eWhat I do is have them all inherit from a common parent (Actor in your case) and call a virtual function *in the collision event* that takes a role as parameter \u003ccode\u003evirtual void Actor::OnCollide(Roles ColliderRole)\u003c/code\u003e. Having an if else chain isnâ€™t a bad choice if you donâ€™t plan to add more roles, but if you do plan then having virtual functions is easier\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-08-30T21:08:08.130Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":37,"readers_count":36,"score":7.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"Actually Permanent","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1165,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33241,"name":"gl.tch method","username":"glitch-method","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/glitch-method/{size}/2552_2.png","created_at":"2019-08-30T22:57:15.619Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003etoo new to give a good code example, but it seems fairly sane considering all roles are being treated as an Actor. you canâ€™t get away from some kind of elaborate matrix where you list out how roleA should behave with roleXYZ, but you may be able to make it â€œneaterâ€â€¦ I may do something like what \u003ca class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/throwawayerino\"\u003e@throwawayerino\u003c/a\u003e mentioned, and/or maintain an array, couple options thereâ€¦ an Nx3 array (role, role, result), so your if block becomes something like\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003e    for n in array:\n        arrayA = array[n,1]\n        arrayB = array[n,2]\n        if (roleA = arrayA \u0026amp; roleB = arrayB]) or (roleB = arrayA \u0026amp; roleA = arrayB) then\n            return array[n,3]\n    next\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ethen youâ€™d have to maintain the array by adding an array[n+1, (new role, arrayA, new result)] for each unique arrayA.\u003cbr\u003e\nor -\u003cbr\u003e\nan XxX array containing only results, like\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003ereturn = array[roleA, roleB]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ethen maintain by adding array[new role, roleB] for each unique roleB,\u003cbr\u003e\nand adding array[roleA, new role] for each unique roleA.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eiâ€™m not sure which would end up messier or bloated if youâ€™re going to add a lot of roles, though. and like I said, iâ€™m newâ€¦ so someone else could probably give you a neater solution. just seemed worth mentioning.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eedit: formatting, iguess my phone doesnâ€™t like me.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-08-30T23:20:07.463Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":37,"readers_count":36,"score":7.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"gl.tch method","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1223,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33258,"name":"Jonathan","username":"Sinoid","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png","created_at":"2019-08-30T23:51:29.047Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eAre you just ignoring sequencing? You can deal with Rock vs Missle and Missle vs Rock in one go by ordering your sides.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003e// sort keys so tests are invariant to parameter sequence\nif (roleB \u0026lt; roleA)\n{\n    swap(roleA, roleB);\n    swap(actorA, actorB);\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eItâ€™s generally easier to just use a table of function pointers with a \u003cem\u003ekey\u003c/em\u003e object for this sort of callback lookup. Using a proper key instead of some if statements makes it easier to deal with the \u003ccode\u003eleftSide = min(roleA, roleB), rightSide = max(roleA, roleB)\u003c/code\u003e youâ€™ll need to do if you want to be invariant to sequence, you deal with it once and never deal with it again - instead of every \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e statement needing to be in the correct order.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-08-30T23:52:43.671Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":35,"readers_count":34,"score":42.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"Jonathan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":669,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33347,"name":"Peter","username":"Spongeloaf","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/spongeloaf/{size}/2527_2.png","created_at":"2019-08-31T17:51:28.813Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eDamn, I like this.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI hadnâ€™t thought of sorting them by comparison, but that should work implicitly if Iâ€™m using an enum class right? If so, Iâ€™ll definitely keep the role matrix, as \u003ca class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/glitch-method\"\u003e@glitch-method\u003c/a\u003e agrees itâ€™s necessary in some capacity, but this will drastically cut down on the umber of cases. Thanks!\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-08-31T17:51:28.813Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":34,"readers_count":33,"score":11.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"Peter","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"username":"Sinoid","name":"Jonathan","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1219,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33350,"name":"é­”å¤§å†œ ğğğ³ ç¾æ‹›èœ","username":"Modanung","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/modanung/{size}/3290_2.png","created_at":"2019-08-31T21:43:30.806Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eIn \u003ca href=\"https://gitlab.com/luckeyproductions/heXon\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003eheXon\u003c/a\u003e I just used things like \u003ccode\u003eif (otherNode-\u0026gt;HasComponent\u0026lt;T\u0026gt;())\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eGetDerivedComponent\u0026lt;Enemy\u0026gt;()\u003c/code\u003e inside \u003ccode\u003eNodeCollisionStart\u003c/code\u003e event handlers. It worked for me, and keeps the logic where it happens. I donâ€™t know about the computational difference, the game \u003cem\u003eis\u003c/em\u003e aptly named \u003cem\u003ehack zone\u003c/em\u003e.\u003cbr\u003e\nSince thereâ€™s a constant race for the pickups in the case of multi-player, it may happen two ships hit a pickup during the same frame. Distances are therefor also taken into account to assure fairness.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-08-31T22:35:58.318Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":35,"readers_count":34,"score":12.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"é­”å¤§å†œ ğğğ³ ç¾æ‹›èœ","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://gitlab.com/luckeyproductions/heXon","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"LucKey Productions / heXon Â· GitLab","clicks":1}],"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"username":"Spongeloaf","name":"Peter","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/spongeloaf/{size}/2527_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":192,"hidden":false,"trust_level":0,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_suspended":true,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33409,"name":"Peter","username":"Spongeloaf","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/spongeloaf/{size}/2527_2.png","created_at":"2019-09-03T14:42:23.220Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/modanung\"\u003e@Modanung\u003c/a\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\nThe only reason I havenâ€™t done the same is that most of my components are re-used among actors, and certain combinations of components need to be handled differently.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI could also make more bespoke components, but I think this is less work for a similar result, in my case anyway.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-09-03T14:42:23.220Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":33,"readers_count":32,"score":11.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"Peter","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"username":"Modanung","name":"é­”å¤§å†œ ğğğ³ ç¾æ‹›èœ","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/modanung/{size}/3290_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1219,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":33410,"name":"","username":"George1","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/g/9e8a1a/{size}.png","created_at":"2019-09-03T15:25:00.608Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSimilar to navigation problem.\u003cbr\u003e\nAdd index to all your component role types.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAdd a 2D matrix as lookup table for your role index components.  Then label 0,1, 2 etc.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis should reduce your combinations of if.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThen just return the lookup value and call the respected function.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ee.g.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNORMAL = 0\u003cbr\u003e\nDETONATE = 1\u003cbr\u003e\nOTHER = 2\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ecollisionType = LookUpCollisionType( ra.index, rb.index);\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eswitch(collisionType )\u003cbr\u003e\ncase NORMAL:\u003cbr\u003e\nDoNormalThing()\u003cbr\u003e\ncase DETONATE:\u003cbr\u003e\nExplodeThing()\u003cbr\u003e\ncase OTHER:\u003cbr\u003e\nDoOtherThing()\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2019-09-04T03:25:16.200Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":36,"readers_count":35,"score":7.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":5533,"topic_slug":"how-to-handle-different-types-of-collisions-with-different-effects","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":